title: For Sale:  GUN SALE WITH NICE PRICE FOR SALE (( The 45 $1500, the M1 Carbine $1000 and the Victory 38 $1000.)))
postcontent:
I have my dads 45, 38, and M1 carbine. I have his discharge papers showing the 45 and 38 checked out to him. The 45 and M1 carbine come with extra stuff. The 38 is a S&W made for the government in October of 1943. I am selling all three for $1000, no trades.
The 45 is a Remington Rand. According to the serial no 1016319 and what I have been told it is a sand cast model. All the items that are in the picture with it were brought home at the same time except for the pair of grips on it,camo holster and the extended clip. The US holster is the one my Dad got with the gun. The rest was all my Dads personal gear issue to him. The three clips are the original clips that came with the gun.
The S&W 38 serial no is V424979 and according to that it was shipped in October of 1943. Guns without a top strap marking usually shipped per contracts with the Defense Supplies Corporation or the U.S. Maritime Commission. This would make sense as my Dad picked up the Mine Sweeper from Puget Sound Naval Shipyard Washington around Christmas 1943. I know this because he shipped out on the Mine Sweeper right after he married my Mom in Puget Sound. He only had a week before he shipped out.
The M1 Carbine was issue to him at the same time. It is an Inland Division of General Motors serial no 46458. The receiver was made somewhere between October, 1941 - April, 1942. The barrel is marked 5-43. The carbine was usually assembled and tested within two or three months after the barrel date. This is a very early one and is quite rare in this shape.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson S&W Model 58 -- Military & Police .41 Mag. Double Action Revolver
postcontent:
LSB#: 121228MM04 

Make: Smith & Wesson 

Model: The .41 Magnum Military & Police – Model 58 

Year of Manufacture: 1968-1969 

Caliber: .41 Magnum 

Action Type: Single and Double Action Swing-Out Cylinder Revolver 

Barrel Length: 4” 

Sights / Optics: The front sight is a fixed, serrated ramp pinned to the solid rib. There is a square notch rear sight milled into the top strap. 

Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are smooth varnished wood with finger grooves. The grain is nicely bookended on the bottom of the grip panels. There are no notable marks, chips, cracks or scratches on the grips, just light handling marks. The grips rate in about Excellent overall condition. 

Type of Finish: Blue 

Finish Originality: Probably refinished. 

Bore Condition: The bore is dark and the rifling is sharp. There is no erosion in the bore. 

Overall Condition: This handgun retains about 99% of its metal finish. There is a drag mark on the cylinder and some very light handling marks and that’s about it. The finish is so good that we have questioned it ourselves, and now believe it to have been re-blued. The screw heads are sharp. The markings are clear. The sides of the hammer and trigger have been nicely jeweled. Overall, this handgun rates in about Excellent condition. 

Mechanics: The single and double actions function correctly. This is a Square Butt, N Frame revolver with a pinned barrel and recessed cylinder. There is a .265” wide checkered service hammer that has had its sides jeweled as well as a .265” wide serrated trigger that also has been jeweled. We did not fire this handgun. 

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: None 

Our Assessment: This is one really pretty revolver! We did some research to try to determine if it had been re-blued at the factory, but came up empty. The lower left side of the grip frame (towards the rear) is marked “ENG” which is unusual in our experience. We wonder if this is related to its being refinished? In any event, this is a .41 Magnum with fixed sights and would make a very sturdy service sidearm, if you were willing to take the chance that it might get scratched. This a very versatile revolver for shooters who are reloaders, with published loads for everything from light accurate target loads to serious self-defense loads to hunting loads. We know there are people who hold a special fondness for this caliber, and expect the successful bidder to cherish this particular Model 58.

title: For Sale:  GUN SALE WITH NICE PRICE FOR SALE (( The 45 $1500, the M1 Carbine $1000 and the Victory 38 $1000.))
postcontent:
I have my dads 45, 38, and M1 carbine. I have his discharge papers showing the 45 and 38 checked out to him. The 45 and M1 carbine come with extra stuff. The 38 is a S&W made for the government in October of 1943. I am selling all three for $1000, no trades.
The 45 is a Remington Rand. According to the serial no 1016319 and what I have been told it is a sand cast model. All the items that are in the picture with it were brought home at the same time except for the pair of grips on it,camo holster and the extended clip. The US holster is the one my Dad got with the gun. The rest was all my Dads personal gear issue to him. The three clips are the original clips that came with the gun.
The S&W 38 serial no is V424979 and according to that it was shipped in October of 1943. Guns without a top strap marking usually shipped per contracts with the Defense Supplies Corporation or the U.S. Maritime Commission. This would make sense as my Dad picked up the Mine Sweeper from Puget Sound Naval Shipyard Washington around Christmas 1943. I know this because he shipped out on the Mine Sweeper right after he married my Mom in Puget Sound. He only had a week before he shipped out.
The M1 Carbine was issue to him at the same time. It is an Inland Division of General Motors serial no 46458. The receiver was made somewhere between October, 1941 - April, 1942. The barrel is marked 5-43. The carbine was usually assembled and tested within two or three months after the barrel date. This is a very early one and is quite rare in this shape.

The S&W 38 serial no is V424979 and according to that it was shipped in October of 1943. Guns without a top strap marking usually shipped per contracts with the Defense Supplies Corporation or the U.S. Maritime Commission. This would make sense as my Dad picked up the Mine Sweeper from Puget Sound Naval Shipyard Washington around Christmas 1943. I know this because he shipped out on the Mine Sweeper right after he married my Mom in Puget Sound. He only had a week before he shipped out.
The M1 Carbine was issue to him at the same time. It is an Inland Division of General Motors serial no 46458. The receiver was made somewhere between October, 1941 - April, 1942. The barrel is marked 5-43. The carbine was usually assembled and tested within two or three months after the barrel date. This is a very early one and is quite rare in this shape.

postcontent:
LSB#: 121228CB04 

Make: Colt 

Model: Single Action Revolver, Artillery Model 

Year of Manufacture: 1881 (Frame) 

Caliber: .45 Colt 

Action Type: Single Action Revolver 

Markings: The top of the barrel is marked “Colt’s Pt. F.A. Mfg. Co. Hartford Ct. U.S.A. “. The left side of the frame is marked “Pat. Sept. 19, 1871 / " July 2,-72 / " Jan. 19,-75" and "U.S." The frame is marked "DFC / 72963", the trigger guard is marked "110081" and the back strap looks renumbered and only "7 ? / 96?" can be seen. The right side of the barrel is marked "7792" (upside down.) The cylinder is marked "D.F.C." 

Barrel Length: 5 1/2" 

Sights / Optics: The front sight is a fixed blade. The rear sight is a notched top strap. 

Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are one piece wood. The panels have thinned, especially at the edges and darkened from age. No cartouches can be seen and the grips have likely been sanded. The wood to metal fit is still acceptable, though a bit shy and loose. The grips nicely match the appearance of the gun. The grips rate in about Good overall condition. 

Type of Finish: Now Patina 

Finish Originality: None Remains 

Bore Condition: The bore is actually better than would be expected, almost bright, and the rifling is pronounced. There is only very mild and very scattered erosion in the bore. 

Overall Condition: This handgun retains about 0% of its metal finish. The pistol has a brown appearance, the back strap showing some possible brown touch up. The rest of the gun shows a lot of patina, a likely refinish at the time of the rebuild and somewhat rounded edges. The metal is generally smooth. The screw heads are only slightly worn. The markings are legible. Overall, this handgun rates in about Fair to Good condition. 

Mechanics: The action functions correctly, the springs are strong and the timing is quite good. There is some play in the lock up. We did not fire this handgun. 

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: None

STG 44 in 22 lr with 25 round magazine. It is all metal and wood made in Germany by GSG (Only thing Poly is the mag on this gun). The StG 44 is a full weight, almost exact replica of the original 8×33 Kurz rifle that is said to be the predecessor to the Kalashnikov AK47, as well as all of the other assault rifles spanning the decades after WWII. location: SIOUX FALLS, South Dakota, United States
postcontent: This appears to be a WWI Colt, but there are no markings on it anywhere so I am assuming that is a lunch box special that seems to be fairly common from back in the teen's and twenty's. Someone did an excellent job of polishing and plating and the finish looks to be an easy 98%. The only thing they seem to have missed was the “dummy scratch”. Luckily the gun is from before they were required to have serial numbers. Then they plated everything down to the grip screws and the two tone lanyard loop magazine. For contrast the hammer and thumb safety are gold plated. The bore is excellent and the grips look like an excellent quality reproduction of the double diamond Colt grips. The plating is in super shape and has no bubbles or pealing. This is a nice shooter Colt with a little bit of flash.
